&gt; 
&gt; This Yukimitsu was finally delivered to me after five weeks. 
&gt; 
&gt; The final story as told to me by Canada Customs was that a postal
&gt; employee brought them the sword on January 24th (it was sent from Japan
&gt; on December 22nd by air), they then released it the same day.
&gt; 
&gt; The final story as told to me by Canada Post was that one of their
&gt; employees searched at Canada Customs and found the sword there. 
&gt; 
&gt; Obviously not both can be true, so someone is covering their ass
&gt; somewhere. 
&gt; 
&gt; Canada Customs was always very good on this whole thing were the ones
&gt; who gave me detailed information about Canada Post that CP didn&#39;t even
&gt; know about itself... information that was required to let me get the
&gt; sword in the end, rather than what Canada Post wanted to do which was to
&gt; write it off as permanently lost. It allowed me to get a message sent to
&gt; the warehouse manager that started the search that immediately turned up
&gt; the sword.
&gt; 
&gt; This identical problem happened to me one year ago in Montreal, with the
&gt; same situation... someone removed a sword from the stream, scanned that
&gt; it was sent to Customs, then it was put aside in someone&#39;s office where
&gt; at the end of three weeks of phone calls and searching it was later
&gt; &quot;found&quot; 15 minutes after I said I was sending the police.
&gt; 
&gt; Needless to say it is Fedex only for me here on in, and I could myself
&gt; lucky to have gotten both pieces back.
&gt; 
&gt; Thanks go to a lot of you who sent me supportive notes. I was pretty
&gt; deep in despair there due to the value and importance of the
&gt; piece. Those notes helped me make it through, so thanks.
